{"title_page": "Ross King (author)", "text_new": "{{other people||Ross King (disambiguation){{!}}Ross King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Ross King\n| image =\n| caption = Ross King\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|7|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Estevan]], Saskatchewan, Canada\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Writer, critic, historian\n| genre = Historical fiction, [[historical non-fiction]]\n| notableworks = ''Domino''\n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| website = \n}}\n'''Ross King''' (born July 16, 1962) is a Canadian novelist and non-fiction writer.  He began his career by writing two works of historical fiction in the 1990s, later turning to non-fiction, and has since written several critically acclaimed and best-selling historical works.\n\n==Career and works==\nKing was born in [[Estevan]], Saskatchewan, Canada and was raised in the nearby village of [[North Portal]].  He received his undergraduate university education at the [[University of Regina]], where in 1984 he completed a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) degree in English Literature.  Continuing his studies at the University of Regina, he received a Master of Arts degree in 1986 upon completing a thesis on the poet [[T. S. Eliot]].  Later he achieved a PhD from [[York University]] in Toronto (1992), where he specialized in eighteenth-century English literature.\n\nKing moved to England to take up a position as a post-doctoral research fellow at [[University College London]].  It was at this time that he began writing his first novel.\n\nKing's first novel, ''Domino'', (1995), tells the story of a castrato singer seen through the experience of an aspiring painter in the London of the 1770s.\n\nIn 1998, King published ''Ex-Libris'', his second work of historical fiction.  Set in London and Prague, it chronicles how a London bookseller's search in the 1660s for a missing manuscript leads him unwittingly into a world of deception and murder.\n\n''Brunelleschi's Dome: The Story of the Great Cathedral in Florence'' (2000) describes how the Italian architect [[Filippo Brunelleschi]] designed what still stands as the largest masonry dome ever built: the dome of the cathedral of [[Santa Maria del Fiore]], completed in 1436.  ''Brunelleschi's Dome'' marked King's transition from novelist to writer of art histories and biographies.<ref name=Globe>{{cite news|last=Barber|first=John|title=Writer Ross King : 'I\u2019m not interested in making things up'|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/writer-ross-king-im-not-interested-in-making-things-up/article5368277/|accessdate=January 30, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=November 16, 2012}}</ref>  ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling,'' (2002), follows the four arduous years during which [[Michelangelo]] painted the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] amid the political and religious intrigues of early sixteenth-century Rome.\n\nKing's next book, ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade That Gave the World Impressionism'' (2006), was met by much critical acclaim and considerable commercial success.  By contrasting the works and lives of the French painters [[Ernest Meissonier]] and [[\u00c9douard Manet]], the book chronicles the dramatic transition by which the [[Impressionism|Impressionist painters]] changed the artistic vision of the late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century. King received Canada's 2006 [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction|Governor-General's Award for Non-Fiction]] for this book.<ref name=Globe/>\n\nHis next project, part of the [[Eminent Lives]] series, was ''Machiavelli: Philosopher of Power'' (2007), a biography of [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli]] in which King illustrates the personal, social and political development of one of history's most famous political theorists.\n\n''Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven'' (2010) looked at the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] organization of Canadian landscape artists that launched Canada's first nationalist art movement in the decades after the First World War.<ref name=Globe/>\n\nFor ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling,'' King was nominated in 2003 for a National Book Critics Circle Award. ''Brunelleschi's Dome'' was on the bestseller lists of the New York Times, the Boston Globe and the San Francisco Chronicle, and was the recipient of several awards including the 2000 Book Sense Nonfiction Book of the Year.\n\nHe was awarded Canada's 2012 [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction]] for ''Leonardo and the Last Supper'', his examination of [[Leonardo da Vinci|da Vinci]]'s iconic [[The Last Supper (Leonardo da Vinci)|15th century religious mural]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|title=Governor General's lit prize winners led by women|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/11/13/gg-lit-awards-winners.html|accessdate=November 13, 2012|newspaper=CBC News|date=November 13, 2012}}</ref> In 2017, he won the [[RBC Taylor Prize]] for his book ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2017/03/06/ross-king-wins-25000-rbc-taylor-prize-for-mad-enchantment.html|title=Ross King wins $25,000 RBC Taylor Prize for \u2018Mad Enchantment\u2019|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nHe lectures frequently in both Europe and North America, and has given guided tours of [[Florence Cathedral]] and of the Sistine Chapel in Rome.<ref>http://www.penguinspeakersbureau.com/speaker/52 Ross King Biography</ref>\n\nKing lives in Woodstock, England with his wife Melanie.<ref>http://www.walkerbooks.com/authors/index.php?cmd=showtitles&author_id=105&author_name=Ross%20King&author_type=2</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2000: Nonfiction Book of the Year citation, Book Sense, for ''Brunelleschi's Dome: How a Renaissance Genius Reinvented Architecture''\n*2003: Governor-General's Literary Award (Canada) nomination for ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling''\n*2003: National Book Critics Circle Award nomination for ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling''\n*2006: Governor-General's Literary Award (Canada) for Non-Fiction for ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade that Gave the World Impressionism''\n*2012: [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction]] for ''Leonardo and the Last Supper''\n*2017: [[RBC Taylor Prize]] for ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies''\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* ''Domino'' (1995)\n* ''Ex-Libris'' (1998)\n* ''Brunelleschi's Dome: The Story of the Great Cathedral in Florence'' (2000)\n* ''[[Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling]]'' (2002)\n* ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade That Gave the World Impressionism'' (2006)\n* ''Machiavelli: Philosopher of Power'' (2007) \n* ''Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven'' (2010)\n* ''[[Leonardo and the Last Supper]]'' (2011)\n* ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added under references heading by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rosskingbooks.com Ross King] \u2013 Ross King's official web site\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=957692}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Ross}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:People from Estevan]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Award-winning non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Ross King (disambiguation){{!}}Ross King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Ross King\n| image =\n| caption = Ross King\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|7|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Estevan]], Saskatchewan, Canada\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Writer, critic, historian\n| genre = Historical fiction, [[historical non-fiction]]\n| notableworks = ''Domino''\n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| website = \n}}\n'''Ross King''' (born July 16, 1962) is a Canadian novelist and non-fiction writer.  He began his career by writing two works of historical fiction in the 1990s, later turning to non-fiction, and has since written several critically acclaimed and best-selling historical works.\n\n==Career and works==\nKing was born in [[Estevan]], Saskatchewan, Canada and was raised in the nearby village of [[North Portal]].  He received his undergraduate university education at the [[University of Regina]], where in 1984 he completed a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) degree in English Literature.  Continuing his studies at the University of Regina, he received a Master of Arts degree in 1986 upon completing a thesis on the poet [[T. S. Eliot]].  Later he achieved a PhD from [[York University]] in Toronto (1992), where he specialized in eighteenth-century English literature.\n\nKing moved to England to take up a position as a post-doctoral research fellow at [[University College London]].  It was at this time that he began writing his first novel.\n\nKing's first novel, ''Domino'', (1995), tells the story of a castrato singer seen through the experience of an aspiring painter in the London of the 1770s.\n\nIn 1998, King published ''Ex-Libris'', his second work of historical fiction.  Set in London and Prague, it chronicles how a London bookseller's search in the 1660s for a missing manuscript leads him unwittingly into a world of deception and murder.\n\n''Brunelleschi's Dome: The Story of the Great Cathedral in Florence'' (2000) describes how the Italian architect [[Filippo Brunelleschi]] designed what still stands as the largest masonry dome ever built: the dome of the cathedral of [[Santa Maria del Fiore]], completed in 1436.  ''Brunelleschi's Dome'' marked King's transition from novelist to writer of art histories and biographies.<ref name=Globe>{{cite news|last=Barber|first=John|title=Writer Ross King : 'I\u2019m not interested in making things up'|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/writer-ross-king-im-not-interested-in-making-things-up/article5368277/|accessdate=January 30, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=November 16, 2012}}</ref>  ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling,'' (2002), follows the four arduous years during which [[Michelangelo]] painted the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] amid the political and religious intrigues of early sixteenth-century Rome.\n\nKing's next book, ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade That Gave the World Impressionism'' (2006), was met by much critical acclaim and considerable commercial success.  By contrasting the works and lives of the French painters [[Ernest Meissonier]] and [[\u00c9douard Manet]], the book chronicles the dramatic transition by which the [[Impressionism|Impressionist painters]] changed the artistic vision of the late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century. King received Canada's 2006 [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction|Governor-General's Award for Non-Fiction]] for this book.<ref name=Globe/>\n\nHis next project, part of the [[Eminent Lives]] series, was ''Machiavelli: Philosopher of Power'' (2007), a biography of [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli]] in which King illustrates the personal, social and political development of one of history's most famous political theorists.\n\n''Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven'' (2010) looked at the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] organization of Canadian landscape artists that launched Canada's first nationalist art movement in the decades after the First World War.<ref name=Globe/>\n\nFor ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling,'' King was nominated in 2003 for a National Book Critics Circle Award. ''Brunelleschi's Dome'' was on the bestseller lists of the New York Times, the Boston Globe and the San Francisco Chronicle, and was the recipient of several awards including the 2000 Book Sense Nonfiction Book of the Year.\n\nHe was awarded Canada's 2012 [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction]] for ''Leonardo and the Last Supper'', his examination of [[Leonardo da Vinci|da Vinci]]'s iconic [[The Last Supper (Leonardo da Vinci)|15th century religious mural]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|title=Governor General's lit prize winners led by women|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/11/13/gg-lit-awards-winners.html|accessdate=November 13, 2012|newspaper=CBC News|date=November 13, 2012}}</ref> In 2017, he won the [[RBC Taylor Prize]] for his book ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2017/03/06/ross-king-wins-25000-rbc-taylor-prize-for-mad-enchantment.html|title=Ross King wins $25,000 RBC Taylor Prize for \u2018Mad Enchantment\u2019|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nHe lectures frequently in both Europe and North America, and has given guided tours of [[Florence Cathedral]] and of the Sistine Chapel in Rome.<ref>http://www.penguinspeakersbureau.com/speaker/52 Ross King Biography</ref>\n\nKing lives in Woodstock, England with his wife Melanie.<ref>http://www.walkerbooks.com/authors/index.php?cmd=showtitles&author_id=105&author_name=Ross%20King&author_type=2</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2000: Nonfiction Book of the Year citation, Book Sense, for ''Brunelleschi's Dome: How a Renaissance Genius Reinvented Architecture''\n*2003: Governor-General's Literary Award (Canada) nomination for ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling''\n*2003: National Book Critics Circle Award nomination for ''Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling''\n*2006: Governor-General's Literary Award (Canada) for Non-Fiction for ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade that Gave the World Impressionism''\n*2012: [[Governor General's Award for English-language non-fiction]] for ''Leonardo and the Last Supper''\n*2017: [[RBC Taylor Prize]] for ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies''\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* ''Domino'' (1995)\n* ''Ex-Libris'' (1998)\n* ''Brunelleschi's Dome: The Story of the Great Cathedral in Florence'' (2000)\n* ''[[Michelangelo and the Pope's Ceiling]]'' (2002)\n* ''The Judgment of Paris: The Revolutionary Decade That Gave the World Impressionism'' (2006)\n* ''Machiavelli: Philosopher of Power'' (2007) \n* ''Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven'' (2010)\n* ''Leonardo and the Last Supper'' (2011)\n* ''Mad Enchantment: Claude Monet and the Painting of the Water Lilies'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added under references heading by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rosskingbooks.com Ross King] \u2013 Ross King's official web site\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=957692}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Ross}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian biographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:People from Estevan]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Award-winning non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Airproofing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_King_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Digital journalism", "text_new": "{{redirect|Internet news|the Usenet forums|Usenet newsgroup}}\n\n'''Digital journalism,''' also known as '''online journalism,''' is a contemporary form of journalism where editorial content is distributed via the [[Internet]], as opposed to publishing via [[Printing|print]] or [[broadcast]]. What constitutes digital journalism is debated by scholars; however, the primary product of journalism, which is news and features on current affairs, is presented solely or in combination as [[Text (literary theory)|text]], [[Digital audio|audio]], [[video]], or some [[Interactive media|interactive forms]] like [[newsgame]]s, and disseminated through [[digital media]] technology.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Franklin|first= Bob |year=2013 |title=Digital Journalism\", 1:1, p. 1. DOI: 10.1080/21670811.2012.740264 |journal= Digital Journalism |volume= 1 |pages= 1\u20135 |doi= 10.1080/21670811.2012.740264 }}</ref><ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 4.</ref>\n\nFewer [[barriers to entry]], lowered distribution costs, and diverse [[computer networking]] technologies have led to the widespread practice of digital journalism.<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=John |year=2000 |title= Journalism in the Digital Age: Theory and Practice for Broadcast, Print and On-line Media |publisher= Taylor & Francis |page= 9 |accessdate=February 10, 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FqBEv0bwBzoC&pg=PR9&dq=widespread+practice+of+digital+journalism#v=onepage&q=widespread%20practice%20of%20digital%20journalism&f=false|isbn=9780240515892 }}</ref> It has democratized the flow of information that was previously controlled by traditional media including newspapers, magazines, radio, and television.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boler|first= Megan |year=2010|title=Digital Media and Democracy: Tactics in Hard Times |publisher= MIT Press |page= 385|accessdate= February 10, 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4bv-eeLkG6YC&dq=democratization+digital+journalism|isbn= 9780262514897 }}</ref>\n\nSome have asserted that a greater degree of creativity can be exercised with digital journalism when compared to traditional journalism and traditional media.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kawamoto|first= Kevin  |year=2003|title= Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism|publisher= Rowman & Littlefield|page=2|accessdate=February 9, 2014|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dG9vHwHyDFUC|isbn= 9780742526815  }}</ref> The digital aspect may be central to the journalistic message and remains, to some extent, within the creative control of the writer, editor, and/or publisher.<ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 2.</ref>\n\nIt has been acknowledged that reports of its growth have tended to be exaggerated.<ref name=2016down>https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/07/23/key-takeaways-state-of-the-news-media-2018/</ref> In fact, a 2019 Pew survey showed of 16% decline of time spent on online news sites since 2016.<ref name=2016down />\n\n==Overview==\n\nThere is no absolute agreement as to what constitutes digital journalism. Mu Lin argues that, \u201cWeb and mobile platforms demand us to adopt a platform-free mindset for an all-inclusive production approach \u2013 create the [digital] contents first, then distribute via appropriate platforms.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mulinblog.com/what-is-digital-first-media-a-primer-for-journalism-students/|title=A primer for journalism students: What is digital-first strategy?|work=MulinBlog: A digital journalism blog}}</ref> The repurposing of print content for an online audience is sufficient for some, while others require content created with the digital medium's unique features like [[hypertext]]uality.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Fondevila |last1=Gasc\u00f3n|first2= Joan |last2=Francesc |first3= Segura|last3= Herlaynne |year=2012|title=Hipertextuality in digital journalism in Colombia |work=Hipertext.net. Anuario Acad\u00e9mico sobre Documentaci\u00f3n Digital y Comunicaci\u00f3n Interactiva (UPF-Digidoc), 10 |issn= 1695-5498 |url= http://www.upf.edu/hipertextnet/en/numero-10/hypertextuality-in-digital-journalism-in-colombia.html}}</ref><ref>Kawamoto, 2005, p. X.</ref> Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n adds multimedia and interactivity to complete the digital journalism essence.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2010). \"Multimedia, digital press and journalistic genres in Catalonia and in Spain: an empirical analysis\". Communication Studies Journal, n. 7, May 2010, pp. 81-95.</ref> For Deuze, online journalism can be functionally differentiated from other kinds of journalism by its technological component which journalists have to consider when creating or displaying content.<ref name=\"auto8\">Deuze 2003, p. 206.</ref> Digital journalistic work may range from purely editorial content like CNN (produced by professional journalists) online to public-connectivity websites like Slashdot (communication lacking formal barriers of entry).<ref>Deuze 2003, p. 207.</ref> The difference of digital journalism from traditional journalism may be in its reconceptualised role of the reporter in relation to audiences and news organizations.<ref name=\"auto2\">Wall 2005, p. 156.</ref> The expectations of society for instant information was important for the evolution of digital journalism<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Carlson\n | first = David\n | editor1-last = Kawamoto\n | editor1-first = Kevin\n | title = Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism\n | chapter = History of Online Journalism\n | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=dG9vHwHyDFUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA31&dq=digital+journalism+history&ots=Ij_PdBGuNf&sig=5ITr4PiO8vV7lEjKprAm93fUnPA#v=onepage&q=digital%20journalism%20history&f=false\n | year = 2003\n | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield\n | location = Lanham, Md.\n }}</ref>\n. However, it is likely that the exact nature and roles of digital journalism will not be fully known for some time.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe first type of digital journalism, called [[teletext]], was invented in the UK in 1970. Teletext is a system allowing viewers to choose which stories they wish to read and see it immediately. The information provided through teletext is brief and instant, similar to the information seen in digital journalism today.  {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The information was broadcast between the frames of a television signal in what was called the Vertical Blanking Interval or VBI.\n\nAmerican journalist, Hunter S. Thompson relied on early digital communication technology beginning by using a fax machine to report from the 1971 US presidential campaign trail as documented in his book [[Fear and Loathing on the Campaign Trail]].\n\nAfter the invention of teletext was the invention of [[videotex]], of which [[Prestel]] was the world's first system, launching commercially in 1979<ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 36.</ref> with various British newspapers such as the [[Financial Times]] lining up to deliver newspaper stories online through it. Videotex closed down in 1986 due to failing to meet end-user demand.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Third Wave of Online Journalism|url= http://www.ojr.org/ojr/future/1019174689.php|publisher=ojr.org}}</ref>\n\nAmerican newspaper companies took notice of the new technology and created their own videotex systems, the largest and most ambitious being Viewtron, a service of Knight-Ridder launched in 1981. Others were Keycom in Chicago and Gateway in Los Angeles. All of them had closed by 1986.\n\nNext came computer Bulletin Board Systems. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, several smaller newspapers started online news services using BBS software and telephone modems. The first of these was the Albuquerque Tribune in 1989.\n\n''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' in September 1992 [[breaking news|broke the news]] of [[Electronic Arts]]' acquisition of [[Origin Systems]] on [[Prodigy (online service)|Prodigy]], before its next issue went to press.<ref name=\"wilson199212\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1992&pub=2&id=101 | title=Anatomy of a Rumor | work=Computer Gaming World | date=1992<!-- -12 --> | accessdate=5 July 2014 | author=Wilson, Johnny L. | pages=210}}</ref> Online news websites began to proliferate in the 1990s.  An early adopter was ''[[The News & Observer]]'' in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] which offered online news as [[Nando]]. Steve Yelvington wrote on the [[Poynter Institute]] website about [[Nando]], owned by The N&O, by saying \"Nando evolved into the first serious, professional [[news site]] on the World Wide Web\".{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} It originated in the early 1990s as \"NandO Land\".  It is believed that a major increase in digital online journalism occurred around this time when the first commercial web browsers, [[Netscape Navigator]] (1994), and [[Internet Explorer]] (1995).<ref name=\"auto4\">Scott 2005, p. 94.</ref> By 1996, most news outlets had an online presence. Although journalistic content was repurposed from original text/video/audio sources without change in substance, it could be consumed in different ways because of its online form through toolbars, topically grouped content, and intertextual links. A twenty-four-hour news cycle and new ways of user-journalist interaction web boards were among the features unique to the digital format. Later, portals such as AOL and Yahoo! and their [[news aggregator]]s (sites that collect and categorize links from news sources) led to news agencies such as The Associated Press to supplying digitally suited content for aggregation beyond the limit of what client news providers could use in the past.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nAlso, ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', was founded in 1995. In 2001 the ''[[American Journalism Review]]'' called ''Salon'' the Internet's \"preeminent independent venue for journalism.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ajr.org/article.asp?id=314 |title=Can Salon Make It? |first= Paul |last=Fahri |magazine=American Journalism Review|volume= March 2001 |accessdate= July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, for the first time, more Americans reported getting their national and international news from the internet, rather than newspapers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tossed By A Gale|work=The Economist|date=May 14, 2009|url=http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=13642689}}{{Subscription}}</ref> Young people aged 18 to 29 now primarily get their news via the Internet, according to a Pew Research Center report.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|last=Peters|first=Meghan|title=Internet Surpasses Television as Main News Source for Young Adults [STUDY].|url=http://mashable.com/2011/01/04/internet-surpasses-television-as-main-news-source-for-young-adults-study/|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref> Audiences to news sites continued to grow due to the launch of new news sites, continued investment in news online by conventional news organizations, and the continued growth in internet audiences overall.<ref name=\"Pew09-5\">{{cite web |title=The State of the Online News Media 2009 |work=Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. |url=http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_online_intro.php?media=5 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316185250/http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_online_intro.php?media=5 |archivedate=2010-03-16 }}</ref> Sixty-five percent of youth now primarily access the news online.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nMainstream news sites are the most widespread form of online newsmedia production.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> As of 2000, the vast majority of journalists in the Western world now use the internet regularly in their daily work.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In addition to mainstream news sites, digital journalism is found in index and category sites (sites without much original content but many links to existing news sites), meta- and comment sites (sites about newsmedia issues like media watchdogs), and [[Virtual community|share and discussion sites]] (sites that facilitate the connection of people, like [[Slashdot]]).<ref>Deuze 2003, p. 208-211.</ref><ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 15.</ref> Blogs are also another digital journalism phenomenon capable of fresh information, ranging from personal sites to those with audiences of hundreds of thousands.<ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 16.</ref> Digital journalism is involved in the cloud journalism<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Fondevila |last1=Gasc\u00f3n|first2= Joan |last2=Francesc |year=2010 |title=El cloud journalism: un nuevo concepto de producci\u00f3n para el periodismo del siglo XXI |journal= Observatorio (OBS*) |volume= 4, N\u00fam. 1 (2010) |pages= 19\u201335 |issn= 1646-5954 |url=http://obs.obercom.pt/index.php/obs/article/view/315/321}}</ref> phenomenon, a constant flow of contents in the Broadband Society.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2009). \"El papel decisivo de la banda ancha en el Espacio Iberoamericano del Conocimiento\". Revista Iberoamericana de Ciencia, Tecnolog\u00eda y Sociedad\u2013CTS, n\u00ba  2 (julio de 2009), pp. 1-15. Portafolio CTS. {{ISSN|1850-0013}}.</ref>\n\nPrior to 2008, the industry had hoped that publishing news online would prove lucrative enough to fund the costs of conventional newsgathering.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newspapers And Thinking the Unthinkable|author=Clay Shirky|date=March 13, 2009|url=http://www.shirky.com/weblog/2009/03/newspapers-and-thinking-the-unthinkable/}}</ref>  In 2008, however, [[online advertising]] began to slow down, and little progress was made towards development of new business models.<ref name=\"Pew09-5\"/>  The Pew [[Project for Excellence in Journalism]] describes its 2008 report on the State of the News Media, its sixth, as its bleakest ever.<ref>\"The State of the News Media\" Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. [http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_overview_intro.php?media=1 Stateofthemedia.org]</ref> Despite the uncertainty, online journalists report expanding newsrooms. They believe advertising is likely to be the best revenue model supporting the production of online news.<ref>\"Online Journalists Optimistic About Revenue and Technology, Concerned About Changing Values\" Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. [http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_survey_intro.php?media=3 Stateofthemedia.org]</ref>\n\nMany news organizations based in other media also distribute news online, but the amount they use of the new medium varies.  Some news organizations use the Web exclusively or as a secondary outlet for their content. The [[Online News Association]], founded in 1999, is the largest organization representing online journalists, with more than 1,700 members whose principal livelihood involves gathering or producing news for digital presentation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journalists.org/?page=onamission|title=Online News Association|author=Online News Association|work=journalists.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Internet challenges traditional news organizations in several ways. Newspapers may lose [[classified advertising]] to websites, which are often targeted by interest instead of geography. These organizations are concerned about real and perceived loss of viewers and circulation to the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pew Research Journalism Project|url=http://www.journalism.org/2014/03/26/state-of-the-news-media-2014-key-indicators-in-media-and-news/|website=Journalism.org|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHyperlocal journalism is journalism within a very small community. Hyperlocal journalism, like other types of digital journalism, is very convenient for the reader and offers more information than former types of journalism. It is free or inexpensive.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | last1 = Rogers\n | first1 = Tony\n | title = What is Hyperlocal Journalism? Sites That Focus On Areas Often Ignored by Larger News Outlets\n | publisher = about.com\n | url = http://journalism.about.com/od/citizenjournalism/a/hyperlocal.htm\n | accessdate=2011-09-12\n}}</ref>\n\n===Reports of Facebook interfering in journalism===\n\nIt has been acknowledged that Facebook has invested heavily in news sources and purchasing time on local news media outlets.<ref name=facebookbust>https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/03/facebooks-siren-call/</ref><ref name=nbcreports /> Tech Crunch journalist Josh Constine even stated in February 2018 that the company \"stole the news business\" and used sponsorship to make many news publishers its \"ghostwriters.\"<ref name=facebookbust /> In January 2019, founder Mark Zuckerberg announced that he will spend $300 million in local news buys over a three year period.<ref name=nbcreports>https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-announces-300-million-investment-local-news-n958726</ref><ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-investing-300-million-to-bolster-local-news/</ref>\n\n==Impact on readers==\nDigital journalism allows for connection and discussion at levels that print does not offer on its own.  People can comment on articles and start discussion boards to discuss articles. Before the Internet, spontaneous discussion between readers who had never met was impossible. The process of discussing a news item is a big portion of what makes for digital journalism.  People add to the story and connect with other people who want to discuss the topic.\n\nDigital journalism creates an opportunity for [[niche audience]]s, allowing people to have more options as to what to view and read.\n\nDigital journalism opens up new ways of storytelling; through the technical components of the new medium, digital journalists can provide a variety of media, such as [[sound|audio]], [[video]], and [[digital photography]].\n\nDigital journalism represents a revolution of how news is consumed by society. Online sources are able to provide quick, efficient, and accurate [[Reporter|reporting]] of breaking news in a matter of seconds, providing society with a synopsis of events as they occur. Throughout the development of the event, journalists are able to feed online sources the information keeping readers up-to-date in mere seconds. The speed in which a story can be posted can affect the accuracy of the reporting in a way that doesn't usually happen in print journalism. Before the emergence of digital journalism the printing process took much more time, allowing for the discovery and correction of errors.\n\nNews consumers must become Web literate and use [[critical thinking]] to evaluate the credibility of sources.  Because it is possible for anyone to write articles and post them on the Internet, the definition of journalism is changing. Because it is becoming increasingly simple for the average person to have an impact in the news world through tools like blogs and even comments on news stories on reputable [[Online newspaper|news websites]], it becomes increasingly difficult to sift through the [[Information overload|massive amount of information]] coming in from the digital area of journalism.\n\nThere are great advantages with digital journalism and the new [[blogging]] evolution that people are becoming accustomed to, but there are disadvantages. For instance, people are used to what they already know and can't always catch up quickly with the new technologies in the 21st century. The goals of print and digital journalism are the same, although different tools are needed to function.\n\nThe interaction between the writer and consumer is new, and this can be credited to digital journalism. There are many ways to get personal thoughts on the Web. There are some disadvantages to this, however, the main one being [[Formal verification|factual information]]. There is a pressing need for accuracy in digital journalism, and until they find a way to press accuracy, they will still face some criticism.\n\nOne major dispute regards the credibility of these online news websites. A digital journalism credibility study performed by the [[Online News Association]] compares the online public credibility ratings to actual media respondent credibility ratings. Looking at a variety of online media sources, the study found that overall the public saw online media as more credible than it actually is.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mjbear.com/presentations/AUSTIN.ppt |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105151127/http://www.mjbear.com/presentations/AUSTIN.ppt |archive-date=2006-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe effects of digital journalism are evident worldwide. This form of journalism has pushed journalists to reform and evolve. Older journalists who are not tech savvy have felt the blunt force of this. In recent months, a number of older journalists have been pushed out and younger journalists brought in because of their lower cost and ability to work in advanced technology settings.\n\n==Impact on publishers==\nMany newspapers, such as ''[[The New York Times]]'', have created [[Online newspaper|online sites]] to remain competitive and have taken advantage of audio, video, and text linking to remain at the top of news consumers' lists as most of the news enthusiasm now reach their base through hand held devices such as smartphones, tablets etc. Hence audio or video backing is a definite advantage.\n\nNewspapers rarely break news stories any more, with most websites reporting on breaking news before the cable news channels.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}} Digital journalism allows for reports to start out vague and generalized, and progress to a better story. Newspapers and TV cable are at a disadvantage because they generally can only put together stories when an ample amount of detail and information are available.  Often, newspapers have to wait for the next day, or even two days later if it is a late-breaking story, before being able to publish it. Newspapers lose a lot of ground to their online counterparts, with [[advertising|ad revenue]] shifting to the Internet, and subscription to the printed paper decreasing. People are now able to find the news they want, when they want, without having to leave their homes or pay to receive the news {{citation needed|date=September 2011}}, even though there are still people who are willing to pay for online journalistic content.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Himma-Kadakas |first1=Marju |last2=K\u00f5uts |first2=Ragne |title=Who Is Willing to Pay for Online Journalistic Content? |journal=Media and Communication |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=106 |doi=10.17645/mac.v3i4.345 |url=https://www.cogitatiopress.com/mediaandcommunication/article/view/345|year=2015 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nBecause of this, many people have viewed digital journalism as the death of journalism.{{who|date=February 2011}} According to communication scholar Nicole Cohen, \"four practices stand out as putting pressure on traditional journalism production: outsourcing, unpaid labour, metrics and measurement, and automation\".<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\">{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|date=2015-04-03|title=From Pink Slips to Pink Slime: Transforming Media Labor in a Digital Age|journal=The Communication Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=98\u2013122|doi=10.1080/10714421.2015.1031996|issn=1071-4421}}</ref> Free advertising on websites such as [[Craigslist]] has transformed how people publicize; the Internet has created a faster, cheaper way for people to get news out, thus creating the shift in ad sales from standard newspapers to the Internet. There has been a substantial effect of digital journalism and media on the newspaper industry, with the creation of new business models.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc; Del Olmo Arriaga, Josep Llu\u00eds and Sierra S\u00e1nchez, Javier (2011). \"New communicative markets, new business models in the digital press\". Tr\u00edpodos (Extra 2011-VI International Conference on Communication and Reality-Life without Media, Universitat Ramon Llull), pp. 301-310.</ref> It is now possible to contemplate a time in the near future when major towns will no longer have a newspaper and when magazines and network news operations will employ no more than a handful of reporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zcommunications.org/the-death-and-life-of-great-american-newspapers-by-john-nichols|title=zcommunications.org Is For Sale|author=|date=|website=www.zcommunications.org}}</ref> Many newspapers and individual print journalists have been forced out of business because of the popularity of digital journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=6973782&page=1|title=Extra, Extra: Is It the End for Newspapers?|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}</ref> The newspapers that have not been willing to be forced out of business have attempted to survive by saving money, laying off staff, shrinking the size of the publications, eliminating editions, as well as partnering with other businesses to share coverage and content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://multimedia.journalism.berkeley.edu/tutorials/digital-transform/print-editions-decline/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927145926/http://multimedia.journalism.berkeley.edu/tutorials/digital-transform/print-editions-decline/ |archive-date=2014-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, one study concluded that most journalists are ready to compete in a digital world and that these journalists believe the transition from print to digital journalism in their newsroom is moving too slowly.<ref>http://www.mediamanagementcenter.org/research/lifebeyondprint.pdf</ref> Some highly specialized positions in the publishing industry have become obsolete. The growth in digital journalism and the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|near collapse of the economy]] has also led to [[Layoff|downsizing]] for those in the industry.\n\nStudents wishing to become journalists now need to be familiar with digital journalism in order to be able to contribute and develop journalism skills. Not only must a journalist analyze their audience and focus on effective communication with them, they have to be quick; news websites are able to update their stories within minutes of the news event. Other skills may include creating a website and uploading information using basic programming skills.\n\nCritics believe digital journalism has made it easier for individuals who are not qualified journalists to misinform<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ekstr\u00f6m|first=Mats|last2=Lewis|first2=Seth C.|last3=Westlund|first3=Oscar|date=2020-01-20|title=Epistemologies of digital journalism and the study of misinformation|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/1461444819856914|journal=New Media & Society|language=en-US|volume=22|issue=2|pages=205\u2013212|doi=10.1177/1461444819856914|issn=1461-4448}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ciampaglia|first=Giovanni Luca|last2=Mantzarlis|first2=Alexios|last3=Maus|first3=Gregory|last4=Menczer|first4=Filippo|date=2018-03-27|title=Research Challenges of Digital Misinformation: Toward a Trustworthy Web|url=https://aaai.org/ojs/index.php/aimagazine/article/view/2783|journal=AI Magazine|language=en|volume=39|issue=1|pages=65\u201374|doi=10.1609/aimag.v39i1.2783|issn=2371-9621}}</ref> the general public. Many believe that this form of journalism has created a number of sites that do not have credible information. Sites such as [[Perez Hilton|PerezHilton.com]] have been criticized for blurring the lines between journalism and opinionated writing.\n\nSome critics believe that newspapers should not switch to a solely Internet-based format, but instead keep a component of print as well as digital.\n\nDigital journalism allows citizens and readers the opportunity to join in on [[threaded discussion]]s relating to a news article that has been read by the public. This offers an excellent source for writers and reporters to decide what is important and what should be omitted in the future. These threads can provide useful information to writers of digital journalism so that future articles can be pruned and improved to possibly create a better article the next time around.\n\n== Implications on traditional Journalism ==\n[[Digitizing|Digitization]] is currently causing many changes to traditional journalistic practices. The labor of journalists, in general, is becoming increasingly dependent on digital journalism. Scholars outline that this is a change to the execution of journalism and not the conception part of the [[Labor process theory|labor process]].<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\">{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6rnebring|first=Henrik|date=2010-02-03|title=Technology and journalism-as-labour: Historical perspectives|journal=Journalism|language=en|volume=11|issue=1|pages=57\u201374|doi=10.1177/1464884909350644}}</ref> They also contend that this is simply the de-skilling of some skills and the up-skilling of others.<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\"/> This theory is in contention to the notion that [[technological determinism]] is negatively effecting [[journalism]], as it should be understood that it is just changing the traditional skill set.<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\"/> Communication scholar Nicole Cohen believes there are several trends putting pressure on this traditional skill set. Some of which being [[outsourcing]], [[algorithm]]s, and [[automation]].<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\"/> Although Cohen believes that technology could be used to improve Journalism, she feels the current trends in digital journalism are so far affecting the practice in a negative way.<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\"/>\n\nThere is also the impact that digital journalism is influencing the uprising of citizen journalism. Because digital journalism takes place online and is contributed mostly by citizens on user-generated content sites, there is competition growing between the two. Citizen journalism allows anyone to post anything, and because of that, journalists are being forced by their employers to publish more news content than before, which often means rushing news stories and failing to verify the source of information.\n\n==Work outside traditional press==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2013}}\nThe Internet has also given rise to more participation by people who are not normally journalists, such as with Indy Media (Max Perez).\n\n[[Bloggers]] write on [[web logs]] or [[blogs]]. Traditional journalists often do not consider bloggers to automatically be journalists. This has more to do with standards and professional practices than the medium. For instance, crowdsourcing and crowdfunding journalism attracts amateur journalists, as well as ambitious professionals that are restrained by the boundaries set by traditional press. However, the implication of these types of journalism is that it disregards the professional norms of journalistic practices that ensures accuracy and impartiality of the content.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunter|first=Andrea|date=2014-11-24|title=Crowdfunding independent and freelance journalism: Negotiating journalistic norms of autonomy and objectivity|journal=New Media & Society|language=en|volume=17|issue=2|pages=272\u2013288|doi=10.1177/1461444814558915}}</ref>  But, {{As of|2005|lc=on}}, blogging has generally gained at least more attention and has led to some effects on mainstream journalism, such as exposing problems related to a television piece about President [[George W. Bush]]'s National Guard Service.\n\nRecent legal judgements have determined that bloggers are entitled to the same protections as other journalists subject to the same responsibilities. In the United States, the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] [https://www.eff.org/cases/apple-v-does/ has been instrumental] in advocating for the [https://www.eff.org/cases/apple-v-does/ rights of journalist bloggers].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appellatecases.courtinfo.ca.gov/search/case/dockets.cfm?dist=6&doc_id=285455&doc_no=H028579|title=California Courts - Appellate Court Case Information|publisher=ca.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Canada]], the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] ruled that:\"[96] A second preliminary question is what the new defence should be called. In arguments before us, the defence was referred to as the responsible journalism test. This has the value of capturing the essence of the defence in succinct style. However, the traditional media are rapidly being complemented by new ways of communicating on matters of public interest, many of them online, which do not involve journalists. These new disseminators of news and information should, absent good reasons for exclusion, be subject to the same laws as established media outlets. I agree with Lord Hoffmann that the new defence is \"available to anyone who publishes material of public interest in any medium\": Jameel, at para. 54.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/7837/index.do|title=Grant v. Torstar Corp. - SCC Cases (Lexum)|author=|date=|website=scc-csc.lexum.com}}</ref>\n\nOther significant tools of on-line journalism are Internet [[Internet forum|forums]], [[discussion boards]] and [[online chat|chat]]s, especially those representing the Internet version of official media. The widespread use of the Internet all over the world created a unique opportunity to create a meeting place for both sides in many conflicts, such as the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] and the [[First Chechen War|First]] and [[Second Chechen War]]s. Often this gives a unique chance to find new, alternative solutions to the conflict, but often the Internet is turned into the battlefield by contradicting parties creating endless \"online battles.\"\n\n[[Internet radio]] and [[podcast]]s are other growing independent media based on the Internet.\n\n==Blogs==\nWith the rise of digital media, there is a move from the traditional journalist to the blogger or amateur journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theendofjournalism.wdfiles.com/local--files/lydiamiljan/lydia+miljan.pdf|title=The file does not exist|author=|date=|website=theendofjournalism.wdfiles.com}}</ref> Blogs can be seen as a new genre of journalism because of their \"narrative style of news characterized by personalization\" that moves away from traditional journalism's approach,<ref>Wall 2005, p. 154.</ref> changing journalism into a more conversational and decentralized type of news.<ref name=\"auto10\">Wall 2005, p. 157.</ref> Blogging has become a large part of the transmitting of news and ideas across cites, states, and countries, and bloggers argue that blogs themselves are now breaking stories.<ref name=\"auto10\"/> Even online news publications have blogs that are written by their affiliated journalists or other respected writers.  Blogging allows readers and journalists to be opinionated about the news and talk about it in an open environment.  Blogs allow comments where some news outlets do not, due to the need to [[Moderation system|constantly monitor]] what is posted.  By allowing comments, the reader can interact with a story instead of just absorbing the words on the screen. According to one 2007 study, 15% of those who read blogs read them for news.<ref>{{cite web|title=Synovate survey: New study shows Americans' blogging behaviour |url=http://www.synovate.com/news/article/2007/08/new-study-shows-americans-blogging-behaviour.html |publisher=synovate.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815015005/http://www.synovate.com/news/article/2007/08/new-study-shows-americans-blogging-behaviour.html |archivedate=2011-08-15 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, many blogs are highly opinionated and have a [[bias]]. Some are not verified to be true. The [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) established guidelines mandating that bloggers disclose any free goods or services they receive from third parties in 2009 in response to a question of the integrity of product and service reviews in the online community.<ref>http://ftc.gov/os/2009/10/091005revisedendorsementguides.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/10/endortest.shtm|title=FTC Publishes Final Guides Governing Endorsements, Testimonials|work=ftc.gov}}</ref>\n\nThe development of blogging communities has partly resulted because of the lack of local news coverage, the spread of misinformation, and the manipulation of news. Blogging platforms are often used as mediums to spread ideas and connect to others with similar mentalities. Anonymity lives within these platforms that circulates different perspectives. Some have postulated that blogs\u2019 usage of public opinions as facts has gained them status and creditability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molek-Kozakowska|first=Katarzyna|date=August 2013|title=Book review: Digital Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/1750481313485398c|journal=Discourse & Communication|language=en-US|volume=7|issue=3|pages=365\u2013367|doi=10.1177/1750481313485398c|issn=1750-4813}}</ref> Memes are often shared on these blogs due to its social phenomenon and its relation to existing subcultures which often attain high engagement. Traditional journalism has helped set the foundation for blogs, which are frequently used to question mainstream media reported by journalist.\n\n==Citizen journalism==\nDigital journalism's lack of a traditional \"editor\" has given rise to [[citizen journalism]]. The early advances that the digital age offered journalism were faster research, easier editing, conveniences, and a faster delivery time for articles. The Internet has broadened the effect that the digital age has on journalism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Waisbord|first=Silvio|date=2019-03-16|title=The 5Ws and 1H of Digital Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/21670811.2018.1545592|journal=Digital Journalism|volume=7|issue=3|pages=351\u2013358|doi=10.1080/21670811.2018.1545592|issn=2167-0811}}</ref> Because of the popularity of the Internet, most people have access and can add their forms of journalism to the information network. This allows anyone who wants to share something they deem important that has happened in their community. Individuals who are not professional journalists who present news through their blogs or websites are often referred to as citizen journalists. One does not need a <!-- college? -->[[Academic degree|degree]] to be a citizen journalist. Citizen journalists are able to publish information that may not be reported otherwise, and the public has a greater opportunity to be informed. Some companies use the information that a citizen journalist relays when they themselves can not access certain situations, for example, in countries where [[freedom of the press]] is limited. Anyone can [[Internet video|record]] events happening and send it anywhere they wish, or put it on their website. Non-profit and grassroots digital journalism sites may have far fewer resources than their corporate counterparts, yet due to digital media are able to have websites that are technically comparable.<ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 15.</ref> Other media outlets can then pick up their story and run with it as they please, thus allowing information to reach wider audiences.\n\nFor citizen journalism to be effective and successful, there needs to be citizen editors. Their role being to solicit other people to provide accurate information and to mediate interactivity among users. An example can be found in the start-up of the South Korean online daily newspaper, [[OhMyNews]], where the founder recruited several hundred volunteer \"citizen reporters\" to write news articles that were edited and processed by four professional journalists.<ref>Bentley 2011, p. 107.</ref>\n\n==News collections==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2013}}\nThe Internet also offers options such as personalized news feeds and [[News aggregator|aggregators]], which compile news from different websites into one site. One of the most popular news aggregators is [[Google News]]. Others include  [[Topix.net]], and [[TheFreeLibrary.com]].\n\nBut, some people see too much personalization as detrimental. For example, some fear that people will have narrower exposure to news, seeking out only those commentators who already agree with them.\n\nAs of March 2005, [[Wikinews]] rewrites articles from other news organizations. Original reporting remains a challenge on the Internet as the burdens of verification and legal risks (especially from plaintiff-friendly jurisdictions like BC) remain high in the absence of any net-wide approach to defamation.<ref>O'Grady v. Superior Court, 44 Cal. Rptr. 3d 72, 139 Cal.App. 4th 1423, modified by O'Grady v. Superior Court, 140 Cal.App. 4th 675b, 2006.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Online newspaper]]\n*[[Open source journalism]]\n*[[n:Main Page|Wikinews]]\n*[[Toons Mag]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bentley, Clyde H. 2011. Citizen journalism: Back to the future? ''[[Geopolitics, History, and International Relations]]'' 3 (1): p.&nbsp;103ff.\n* Deuze, Mark. 2003. The web and its journalisms: Considering the consequences of different types of newsmedia online. ''[[New Media & Society]]'' 5 (2): 203-230.\n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2009). El papel decisivo de la banda ancha en el Espacio Iberoamericano del Conocimiento. ''Revista Iberoamericana de Ciencia, Tecnolog\u00eda y Sociedad\u2013CTS'', n. 2, pp.&nbsp;1\u201315.  \n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2010). El cloud journalism: un nuevo concepto de producci\u00f3n para el periodismo del siglo XXI. ''Observatorio (OBS*) Journal'', v. 4, n. 1 (2010), pp.&nbsp;19\u201335. \n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc; Del Olmo Arriaga, Josep Llu\u00eds and Sierra S\u00e1nchez, Javier (2011). New communicative markets, new business models in the [https://thedigitalji.com/ digital] press. ''Tr\u00edpodos'' (Extra 2011-VI International Conference on Communication and Reality-Life without Media, Universitat Ramon Llull), pp.&nbsp;301\u2013310. \n* Kawamoto, Kevin. 2003. ''Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism''. Lanham, Md.: Rowman & Littlefield\n* [http://www.ojr.org/ojr/future/1019174689.php Online Journalism Review. 2002. The third wave of online journalism. Online Journalism Review]\n* [http://journalism.about.com/od/citizenjournalism/a/hyperlocal.htm Rogers, Tony. What is hyperlocal journalism? Sites that focus on areas often ignored by larger news outlets\" about.com], accessdate= September 12, 2011\n* Scott, Ben. 2005. A contemporary history of digital journalism. ''[[Television & New Media]]'' 6 (1): 89-126\n* Wall, Melissa. 2005. \"Blogs of war: Weblogs as news.\" ''Journalism'' 6 (2): 153-172\n\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:Online journalism| ]]\n[[Category:Types of journalism]]\n[[Category:Citizen journalism]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Citizen media]]\n[[Category:New media]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Internet news|the Usenet forums|Usenet newsgroup}}\n\n'''Digital journalism,''' also known as '''online journalism,''' is a contemporary form of journalism where editorial content is distributed via the [[Internet]], as opposed to publishing via [[Printing|print]] or [[broadcast]]. What constitutes digital journalism is debated by scholars; however, the primary product of journalism, which is news and features on current affairs, is presented solely or in combination as [[Text (literary theory)|text]], [[Digital audio|audio]], [[video]], or some [[Interactive media|interactive forms]] like [[newsgame]]s, and disseminated through [[digital media]] technology.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Franklin|first= Bob |year=2013 |title=Digital Journalism\", 1:1, p. 1. DOI: 10.1080/21670811.2012.740264 |journal= Digital Journalism |volume= 1 |pages= 1\u20135 |doi= 10.1080/21670811.2012.740264 }}</ref><ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 4.</ref>\n\nFewer [[barriers to entry]], lowered distribution costs, and diverse [[computer networking]] technologies have led to the widespread practice of digital journalism.<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=John |year=2000 |title= Journalism in the Digital Age: Theory and Practice for Broadcast, Print and On-line Media |publisher= Taylor & Francis |page= 9 |accessdate=February 10, 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FqBEv0bwBzoC&pg=PR9&dq=widespread+practice+of+digital+journalism#v=onepage&q=widespread%20practice%20of%20digital%20journalism&f=false|isbn=9780240515892 }}</ref> It has democratized the flow of information that was previously controlled by traditional media including newspapers, magazines, radio, and television.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boler|first= Megan |year=2010|title=Digital Media and Democracy: Tactics in Hard Times |publisher= MIT Press |page= 385|accessdate= February 10, 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4bv-eeLkG6YC&dq=democratization+digital+journalism|isbn= 9780262514897 }}</ref>\n\nSome have asserted that a greater degree of creativity can be exercised with digital journalism when compared to traditional journalism and traditional media.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kawamoto|first= Kevin  |year=2003|title= Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism|publisher= Rowman & Littlefield|page=2|accessdate=February 9, 2014|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dG9vHwHyDFUC|isbn= 9780742526815  }}</ref> The digital aspect may be central to the journalistic message and remains, to some extent, within the creative control of the writer, editor, and/or publisher.<ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 2.</ref>\n\nIt has been acknowledged that reports of its growth have tended to be exaggerated.<ref name=2016down>https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/07/23/key-takeaways-state-of-the-news-media-2018/</ref> In fact, a 2019 Pew survey showed of 16% decline of time spent on online news sites since 2016.<ref name=2016down />\n\n==Overview==\n\nThere is no absolute agreement as to what constitutes digital journalism. Mu Lin argues that, \u201cWeb and mobile platforms demand us to adopt a platform-free mindset for an all-inclusive production approach \u2013 create the [digital] contents first, then distribute via appropriate platforms.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mulinblog.com/what-is-digital-first-media-a-primer-for-journalism-students/|title=A primer for journalism students: What is digital-first strategy?|work=MulinBlog: A digital journalism blog}}</ref> The repurposing of print content for an online audience is sufficient for some, while others require content created with the digital medium's unique features like [[hypertext]]uality.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Fondevila |last1=Gasc\u00f3n|first2= Joan |last2=Francesc |first3= Segura|last3= Herlaynne |year=2012|title=Hipertextuality in digital journalism in Colombia |work=Hipertext.net. Anuario Acad\u00e9mico sobre Documentaci\u00f3n Digital y Comunicaci\u00f3n Interactiva (UPF-Digidoc), 10 |issn= 1695-5498 |url= http://www.upf.edu/hipertextnet/en/numero-10/hypertextuality-in-digital-journalism-in-colombia.html}}</ref><ref>Kawamoto, 2005, p. X.</ref> Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n adds multimedia and interactivity to complete the digital journalism essence.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2010). \"Multimedia, digital press and journalistic genres in Catalonia and in Spain: an empirical analysis\". Communication Studies Journal, n. 7, May 2010, pp. 81-95.</ref> For Deuze, online journalism can be functionally differentiated from other kinds of journalism by its technological component which journalists have to consider when creating or displaying content.<ref name=\"auto8\">Deuze 2003, p. 206.</ref> Digital journalistic work may range from purely editorial content like CNN (produced by professional journalists) online to public-connectivity websites like Slashdot (communication lacking formal barriers of entry).<ref>Deuze 2003, p. 207.</ref> The difference of digital journalism from traditional journalism may be in its reconceptualised role of the reporter in relation to audiences and news organizations.<ref name=\"auto2\">Wall 2005, p. 156.</ref> The expectations of society for instant information was important for the evolution of digital journalism<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Carlson\n | first = David\n | editor1-last = Kawamoto\n | editor1-first = Kevin\n | title = Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism\n | chapter = History of Online Journalism\n | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=dG9vHwHyDFUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA31&dq=digital+journalism+history&ots=Ij_PdBGuNf&sig=5ITr4PiO8vV7lEjKprAm93fUnPA#v=onepage&q=digital%20journalism%20history&f=false\n | year = 2003\n | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield\n | location = Lanham, Md.\n }}</ref>\n. However, it is likely that the exact nature and roles of digital journalism will not be fully known for some time.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe first type of digital journalism, called [[teletext]], was invented in the UK in 1970. Teletext is a system allowing viewers to choose which stories they wish to read and see it immediately. The information provided through teletext is brief and instant, similar to the information seen in digital journalism today.  {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The information was broadcast between the frames of a television signal in what was called the Vertical Blanking Interval or VBI.\n\nAmerican journalist, Hunter S. Thompson relied on early digital communication technology beginning by using a fax machine to report from the 1971 US presidential campaign trail as documented in his book [[Fear and Loathing on the Campaign Trail]].\n\nAfter the invention of teletext was the invention of [[videotex]], of which [[Prestel]] was the world's first system, launching commercially in 1979<ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 36.</ref> with various British newspapers such as the [[Financial Times]] lining up to deliver newspaper stories online through it. Videotex closed down in 1986 due to failing to meet end-user demand.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Third Wave of Online Journalism|url= http://www.ojr.org/ojr/future/1019174689.php|publisher=ojr.org}}</ref>\n\nAmerican newspaper companies took notice of the new technology and created their own videotex systems, the largest and most ambitious being Viewtron, a service of Knight-Ridder launched in 1981. Others were Keycom in Chicago and Gateway in Los Angeles. All of them had closed by 1986.\n\nNext came computer Bulletin Board Systems. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, several smaller newspapers started online news services using BBS software and telephone modems. The first of these was the Albuquerque Tribune in 1989.\n\n''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' in September 1992 [[breaking news|broke the news]] of [[Electronic Arts]]' acquisition of [[Origin Systems]] on [[Prodigy (online service)|Prodigy]], before its next issue went to press.<ref name=\"wilson199212\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1992&pub=2&id=101 | title=Anatomy of a Rumor | work=Computer Gaming World | date=1992<!-- -12 --> | accessdate=5 July 2014 | author=Wilson, Johnny L. | pages=210}}</ref> Online news websites began to proliferate in the 1990s.  An early adopter was ''[[The News & Observer]]'' in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] which offered online news as [[Nando]]. Steve Yelvington wrote on the [[Poynter Institute]] website about [[Nando]], owned by The N&O, by saying \"Nando evolved into the first serious, professional [[news site]] on the World Wide Web\".{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} It originated in the early 1990s as \"NandO Land\".  It is believed that a major increase in digital online journalism occurred around this time when the first commercial web browsers, [[Netscape Navigator]] (1994), and [[Internet Explorer]] (1995).<ref name=\"auto4\">Scott 2005, p. 94.</ref> By 1996, most news outlets had an online presence. Although journalistic content was repurposed from original text/video/audio sources without change in substance, it could be consumed in different ways because of its online form through toolbars, topically grouped content, and intertextual links. A twenty-four-hour news cycle and new ways of user-journalist interaction web boards were among the features unique to the digital format. Later, portals such as AOL and Yahoo! and their [[news aggregator]]s (sites that collect and categorize links from news sources) led to news agencies such as The Associated Press to supplying digitally suited content for aggregation beyond the limit of what client news providers could use in the past.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nAlso, ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', was founded in 1995. In 2001 the ''[[American Journalism Review]]'' called ''Salon'' the Internet's \"preeminent independent venue for journalism.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ajr.org/article.asp?id=314 |title=Can Salon Make It? |first= Paul |last=Fahri |magazine=American Journalism Review|volume= March 2001 |accessdate= July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, for the first time, more Americans reported getting their national and international news from the internet, rather than newspapers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tossed By A Gale|work=The Economist|date=May 14, 2009|url=http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=13642689}}{{Subscription}}</ref> Young people aged 18 to 29 now primarily get their news via the Internet, according to a Pew Research Center report.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|last=Peters|first=Meghan|title=Internet Surpasses Television as Main News Source for Young Adults [STUDY].|url=http://mashable.com/2011/01/04/internet-surpasses-television-as-main-news-source-for-young-adults-study/|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref> Audiences to news sites continued to grow due to the launch of new news sites, continued investment in news online by conventional news organizations, and the continued growth in internet audiences overall.<ref name=\"Pew09-5\">{{cite web |title=The State of the Online News Media 2009 |work=Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. |url=http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_online_intro.php?media=5 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316185250/http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_online_intro.php?media=5 |archivedate=2010-03-16 }}</ref> Sixty-five percent of youth now primarily access the news online.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nMainstream news sites are the most widespread form of online newsmedia production.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> As of 2000, the vast majority of journalists in the Western world now use the internet regularly in their daily work.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In addition to mainstream news sites, digital journalism is found in index and category sites (sites without much original content but many links to existing news sites), meta- and comment sites (sites about newsmedia issues like media watchdogs), and [[Virtual community|share and discussion sites]] (sites that facilitate the connection of people, like [[Slashdot]]).<ref>Deuze 2003, p. 208-211.</ref><ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 15.</ref> Blogs are also another digital journalism phenomenon capable of fresh information, ranging from personal sites to those with audiences of hundreds of thousands.<ref>Kawamoto 2005, p. 16.</ref> Digital journalism is involved in the cloud journalism<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Fondevila |last1=Gasc\u00f3n|first2= Joan |last2=Francesc |year=2010 |title=El cloud journalism: un nuevo concepto de producci\u00f3n para el periodismo del siglo XXI |journal= Observatorio (OBS*) |volume= 4, N\u00fam. 1 (2010) |pages= 19\u201335 |issn= 1646-5954 |url=http://obs.obercom.pt/index.php/obs/article/view/315/321}}</ref> phenomenon, a constant flow of contents in the Broadband Society.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2009). \"El papel decisivo de la banda ancha en el Espacio Iberoamericano del Conocimiento\". Revista Iberoamericana de Ciencia, Tecnolog\u00eda y Sociedad\u2013CTS, n\u00ba  2 (julio de 2009), pp. 1-15. Portafolio CTS. {{ISSN|1850-0013}}.</ref>\n\nPrior to 2008, the industry had hoped that publishing news online would prove lucrative enough to fund the costs of conventional newsgathering.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newspapers And Thinking the Unthinkable|author=Clay Shirky|date=March 13, 2009|url=http://www.shirky.com/weblog/2009/03/newspapers-and-thinking-the-unthinkable/}}</ref>  In 2008, however, [[online advertising]] began to slow down, and little progress was made towards development of new business models.<ref name=\"Pew09-5\"/>  The Pew [[Project for Excellence in Journalism]] describes its 2008 report on the State of the News Media, its sixth, as its bleakest ever.<ref>\"The State of the News Media\" Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. [http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_overview_intro.php?media=1 Stateofthemedia.org]</ref> Despite the uncertainty, online journalists report expanding newsrooms. They believe advertising is likely to be the best revenue model supporting the production of online news.<ref>\"Online Journalists Optimistic About Revenue and Technology, Concerned About Changing Values\" Pew Project For Excellence in Journalism. [http://www.stateofthemedia.org/2009/narrative_survey_intro.php?media=3 Stateofthemedia.org]</ref>\n\nMany news organizations based in other media also distribute news online, but the amount they use of the new medium varies.  Some news organizations use the Web exclusively or as a secondary outlet for their content. The [[Online News Association]], founded in 1999, is the largest organization representing online journalists, with more than 1,700 members whose principal livelihood involves gathering or producing news for digital presentation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://journalists.org/?page=onamission|title=Online News Association|author=Online News Association|work=journalists.org}}</ref>\n\nThe Internet challenges traditional news organizations in several ways. Newspapers may lose [[classified advertising]] to websites, which are often targeted by interest instead of geography. These organizations are concerned about real and perceived loss of viewers and circulation to the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pew Research Journalism Project|url=http://www.journalism.org/2014/03/26/state-of-the-news-media-2014-key-indicators-in-media-and-news/|website=Journalism.org|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHyperlocal journalism is journalism within a very small community. Hyperlocal journalism, like other types of digital journalism, is very convenient for the reader and offers more information than former types of journalism. It is free or inexpensive.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | last1 = Rogers\n | first1 = Tony\n | title = What is Hyperlocal Journalism? Sites That Focus On Areas Often Ignored by Larger News Outlets\n | publisher = about.com\n | url = http://journalism.about.com/od/citizenjournalism/a/hyperlocal.htm\n | accessdate=2011-09-12\n}}</ref>\n\n===Reports of Facebook interfering in journalism===\n\nIt has been acknowledged that Facebook has invested heavily in news sources and purchasing time on local news media outlets.<ref name=facebookbust>https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/03/facebooks-siren-call/</ref><ref name=nbcreports /> Tech Crunch journalist Josh Constine even stated in February 2018 that the company \"stole the news business\" and used sponsorship to make many news publishers its \"ghostwriters.\"<ref name=facebookbust /> In January 2019, founder Mark Zuckerberg announced that he will spend $300 million in local news buys over a three year period.<ref name=nbcreports>https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-announces-300-million-investment-local-news-n958726</ref><ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-investing-300-million-to-bolster-local-news/</ref>\n\n==Impact on readers==\nDigital journalism allows for connection and discussion at levels that print does not offer on its own.  People can comment on articles and start discussion boards to discuss articles. Before the Internet, spontaneous discussion between readers who had never met was impossible. The process of discussing a news item is a big portion of what makes for digital journalism.  People add to the story and connect with other people who want to discuss the topic.\n\nDigital journalism creates an opportunity for [[niche audience]]s, allowing people to have more options as to what to view and read.\n\nDigital journalism opens up new ways of storytelling; through the technical components of the new medium, digital journalists can provide a variety of media, such as [[sound|audio]], [[video]], and [[digital photography]].\n\nDigital journalism represents a revolution of how news is consumed by society. Online sources are able to provide quick, efficient, and accurate [[Reporter|reporting]] of breaking news in a matter of seconds, providing society with a synopsis of events as they occur. Throughout the development of the event, journalists are able to feed online sources the information keeping readers up-to-date in mere seconds. The speed in which a story can be posted can affect the accuracy of the reporting in a way that doesn't usually happen in print journalism. Before the emergence of digital journalism the printing process took much more time, allowing for the discovery and correction of errors.\n\nNews consumers must become Web literate and use [[critical thinking]] to evaluate the credibility of sources.  Because it is possible for anyone to write articles and post them on the Internet, the definition of journalism is changing. Because it is becoming increasingly simple for the average person to have an impact in the news world through tools like blogs and even comments on news stories on reputable [[Online newspaper|news websites]], it becomes increasingly difficult to sift through the [[Information overload|massive amount of information]] coming in from the digital area of journalism.\n\nThere are great advantages with digital journalism and the new [[blogging]] evolution that people are becoming accustomed to, but there are disadvantages. For instance, people are used to what they already know and can't always catch up quickly with the new technologies in the 21st century. The goals of print and digital journalism are the same, although different tools are needed to function.\n\nThe interaction between the writer and consumer is new, and this can be credited to digital journalism. There are many ways to get personal thoughts on the Web. There are some disadvantages to this, however, the main one being [[Formal verification|factual information]]. There is a pressing need for accuracy in digital journalism, and until they find a way to press accuracy, they will still face some criticism.\n\nOne major dispute regards the credibility of these online news websites. A digital journalism credibility study performed by the [[Online News Association]] compares the online public credibility ratings to actual media respondent credibility ratings. Looking at a variety of online media sources, the study found that overall the public saw online media as more credible than it actually is.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mjbear.com/presentations/AUSTIN.ppt |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105151127/http://www.mjbear.com/presentations/AUSTIN.ppt |archive-date=2006-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe effects of digital journalism are evident worldwide. This form of journalism has pushed journalists to reform and evolve. Older journalists who are not tech savvy have felt the blunt force of this. In recent months, a number of older journalists have been pushed out and younger journalists brought in because of their lower cost and ability to work in advanced technology settings.\n\n==Impact on publishers==\nMany newspapers, such as ''[[The New York Times]]'', have created [[Online newspaper|online sites]] to remain competitive and have taken advantage of audio, video, and text linking to remain at the top of news consumers' lists as most of the news enthusiasm now reach their base through hand held devices such as smartphones, tablets etc. Hence audio or video backing is a definite advantage.\n\nNewspapers rarely break news stories any more, with most websites reporting on breaking news before the cable news channels.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}} Digital journalism allows for reports to start out vague and generalized, and progress to a better story. Newspapers and TV cable are at a disadvantage because they generally can only put together stories when an ample amount of detail and information are available.  Often, newspapers have to wait for the next day, or even two days later if it is a late-breaking story, before being able to publish it. Newspapers lose a lot of ground to their online counterparts, with [[advertising|ad revenue]] shifting to the Internet, and subscription to the printed paper decreasing. People are now able to find the news they want, when they want, without having to leave their homes or pay to receive the news {{citation needed|date=September 2011}}, even though there are still people who are willing to pay for online journalistic content.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Himma-Kadakas |first1=Marju |last2=K\u00f5uts |first2=Ragne |title=Who Is Willing to Pay for Online Journalistic Content? |journal=Media and Communication |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=106 |doi=10.17645/mac.v3i4.345 |url=https://www.cogitatiopress.com/mediaandcommunication/article/view/345|year=2015 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nBecause of this, many people have viewed digital journalism as the death of journalism.{{who|date=February 2011}} According to communication scholar Nicole Cohen, \"four practices stand out as putting pressure on traditional journalism production: outsourcing, unpaid labour, metrics and measurement, and automation\".<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\">{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|date=2015-04-03|title=From Pink Slips to Pink Slime: Transforming Media Labor in a Digital Age|journal=The Communication Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=98\u2013122|doi=10.1080/10714421.2015.1031996|issn=1071-4421}}</ref> Free advertising on websites such as [[Craigslist]] has transformed how people publicize; the Internet has created a faster, cheaper way for people to get news out, thus creating the shift in ad sales from standard newspapers to the Internet. There has been a substantial effect of digital journalism and media on the newspaper industry, with the creation of new business models.<ref>Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc; Del Olmo Arriaga, Josep Llu\u00eds and Sierra S\u00e1nchez, Javier (2011). \"New communicative markets, new business models in the digital press\". Tr\u00edpodos (Extra 2011-VI International Conference on Communication and Reality-Life without Media, Universitat Ramon Llull), pp. 301-310.</ref> It is now possible to contemplate a time in the near future when major towns will no longer have a newspaper and when magazines and network news operations will employ no more than a handful of reporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zcommunications.org/the-death-and-life-of-great-american-newspapers-by-john-nichols|title=zcommunications.org Is For Sale|author=|date=|website=www.zcommunications.org}}</ref> Many newspapers and individual print journalists have been forced out of business because of the popularity of digital journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=6973782&page=1|title=Extra, Extra: Is It the End for Newspapers?|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}</ref> The newspapers that have not been willing to be forced out of business have attempted to survive by saving money, laying off staff, shrinking the size of the publications, eliminating editions, as well as partnering with other businesses to share coverage and content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://multimedia.journalism.berkeley.edu/tutorials/digital-transform/print-editions-decline/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927145926/http://multimedia.journalism.berkeley.edu/tutorials/digital-transform/print-editions-decline/ |archive-date=2014-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, one study concluded that most journalists are ready to compete in a digital world and that these journalists believe the transition from print to digital journalism in their newsroom is moving too slowly.<ref>http://www.mediamanagementcenter.org/research/lifebeyondprint.pdf</ref> Some highly specialized positions in the publishing industry have become obsolete. The growth in digital journalism and the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|near collapse of the economy]] has also led to [[Layoff|downsizing]] for those in the industry.\n\nStudents wishing to become journalists now need to be familiar with digital journalism in order to be able to contribute and develop journalism skills. Not only must a journalist analyze their audience and focus on effective communication with them, they have to be quick; news websites are able to update their stories within minutes of the news event. Other skills may include creating a website and uploading information using basic programming skills.\n\nCritics believe digital journalism has made it easier for individuals who are not qualified journalists to misinform<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ekstr\u00f6m|first=Mats|last2=Lewis|first2=Seth C.|last3=Westlund|first3=Oscar|date=2020-01-20|title=Epistemologies of digital journalism and the study of misinformation|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/1461444819856914|journal=New Media & Society|language=en-US|volume=22|issue=2|pages=205\u2013212|doi=10.1177/1461444819856914|issn=1461-4448}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ciampaglia|first=Giovanni Luca|last2=Mantzarlis|first2=Alexios|last3=Maus|first3=Gregory|last4=Menczer|first4=Filippo|date=2018-03-27|title=Research Challenges of Digital Misinformation: Toward a Trustworthy Web|url=https://aaai.org/ojs/index.php/aimagazine/article/view/2783|journal=AI Magazine|language=en|volume=39|issue=1|pages=65\u201374|doi=10.1609/aimag.v39i1.2783|issn=2371-9621}}</ref> the general public. Many believe that this form of journalism has created a number of sites that do not have credible information. Sites such as [[Perez Hilton|PerezHilton.com]] have been criticized for blurring the lines between journalism and opinionated writing.\n\nSome critics believe that newspapers should not switch to a solely Internet-based format, but instead keep a component of print as well as digital.\n\nDigital journalism allows citizens and readers the opportunity to join in on [[threaded discussion]]s relating to a news article that has been read by the public. This offers an excellent source for writers and reporters to decide what is important and what should be omitted in the future. These threads can provide useful information to writers of digital journalism so that future articles can be pruned and improved to possibly create a better article the next time around.\n\n== Implications on traditional Journalism ==\n[[Digitizing|Digitization]] is currently causing many changes to traditional journalistic practices. The labor of journalists, in general, is becoming increasingly dependent on digital journalism. Scholars outline that this is a change to the execution of journalism and not the conception part of the [[Labor process theory|labor process]].<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\">{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6rnebring|first=Henrik|date=2010-02-03|title=Technology and journalism-as-labour: Historical perspectives|journal=Journalism|language=en|volume=11|issue=1|pages=57\u201374|doi=10.1177/1464884909350644}}</ref> They also contend that this is simply the de-skilling of some skills and the up-skilling of others.<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\"/> This theory is in contention to the notion that [[technological determinism]] is negatively effecting [[journalism]], as it should be understood that it is just changing the traditional skill set.<ref name=\"\u00d6rnebring 57\u201374\"/> Communication scholar Nicole Cohen believes there are several trends putting pressure on this traditional skill set. Some of which being [[outsourcing]], [[algorithm]]s, and [[automation]].<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\"/> Although Cohen believes that technology could be used to improve Journalism, she feels the current trends in digital journalism are so far affecting the practice in a negative way.<ref name=\"Cohen 98\u2013122\"/>\n\nThere is also the impact that digital journalism is influencing the uprising of citizen journalism. Because digital journalism takes place online and is contributed mostly by citizens on user-generated content sites, there is competition growing between the two. Citizen journalism allows anyone to post anything, and because of that, journalists are being forced by their employers to publish more news content than before, which often means rushing news stories and failing to verify the source of information.\n\n==Work outside traditional press==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2013}}\nThe Internet has also given rise to more participation by people who are not normally journalists, such as with Indy Media (Max Perez).\n\n[[Bloggers]] write on [[web logs]] or [[blogs]]. Traditional journalists often do not consider bloggers to automatically be journalists. This has more to do with standards and professional practices than the medium. For instance, crowdsourcing and crowdfunding journalism attracts amateur journalists, as well as ambitious professionals that are restrained by the boundaries set by traditional press. However, the implication of these types of journalism is that it disregards the professional norms of journalistic practices that ensures accuracy and impartiality of the content.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunter|first=Andrea|date=2014-11-24|title=Crowdfunding independent and freelance journalism: Negotiating journalistic norms of autonomy and objectivity|journal=New Media & Society|language=en|volume=17|issue=2|pages=272\u2013288|doi=10.1177/1461444814558915}}</ref>  But, {{As of|2005|lc=on}}, blogging has generally gained at least more attention and has led to some effects on mainstream journalism, such as exposing problems related to a television piece about President [[George W. Bush]]'s National Guard Service.\n\nRecent legal judgements have determined that bloggers are entitled to the same protections as other journalists subject to the same responsibilities. In the United States, the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] [https://www.eff.org/cases/apple-v-does/ has been instrumental] in advocating for the [https://www.eff.org/cases/apple-v-does/ rights of journalist bloggers].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appellatecases.courtinfo.ca.gov/search/case/dockets.cfm?dist=6&doc_id=285455&doc_no=H028579|title=California Courts - Appellate Court Case Information|publisher=ca.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Canada]], the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] ruled that:\"[96] A second preliminary question is what the new defence should be called. In arguments before us, the defence was referred to as the responsible journalism test. This has the value of capturing the essence of the defence in succinct style. However, the traditional media are rapidly being complemented by new ways of communicating on matters of public interest, many of them online, which do not involve journalists. These new disseminators of news and information should, absent good reasons for exclusion, be subject to the same laws as established media outlets. I agree with Lord Hoffmann that the new defence is \"available to anyone who publishes material of public interest in any medium\": Jameel, at para. 54.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/7837/index.do|title=Grant v. Torstar Corp. - SCC Cases (Lexum)|author=|date=|website=scc-csc.lexum.com}}</ref>\n\nOther significant tools of on-line journalism are Internet [[Internet forum|forums]], [[discussion boards]] and [[online chat|chat]]s, especially those representing the Internet version of official media. The widespread use of the Internet all over the world created a unique opportunity to create a meeting place for both sides in many conflicts, such as the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] and the [[First Chechen War|First]] and [[Second Chechen War]]s. Often this gives a unique chance to find new, alternative solutions to the conflict, but often the Internet is turned into the battlefield by contradicting parties creating endless \"online battles.\"\n\n[[Internet radio]] and [[podcast]]s are other growing independent media based on the Internet.\n\n==Blogs==\nWith the rise of digital media, there is a move from the traditional journalist to the blogger or amateur journalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theendofjournalism.wdfiles.com/local--files/lydiamiljan/lydia+miljan.pdf|title=The file does not exist|author=|date=|website=theendofjournalism.wdfiles.com}}</ref> Blogs can be seen as a new genre of journalism because of their \"narrative style of news characterized by personalization\" that moves away from traditional journalism's approach,<ref>Wall 2005, p. 154.</ref> changing journalism into a more conversational and decentralized type of news.<ref name=\"auto10\">Wall 2005, p. 157.</ref> Blogging has become a large part of the transmitting of news and ideas across cites, states, and countries, and bloggers argue that blogs themselves are now breaking stories.<ref name=\"auto10\"/> Even online news publications have blogs that are written by their affiliated journalists or other respected writers.  Blogging allows readers and journalists to be opinionated about the news and talk about it in an open environment.  Blogs allow comments where some news outlets do not, due to the need to [[Moderation system|constantly monitor]] what is posted.  By allowing comments, the reader can interact with a story instead of just absorbing the words on the screen. According to one 2007 study, 15% of those who read blogs read them for news.<ref>{{cite web|title=Synovate survey: New study shows Americans' blogging behaviour |url=http://www.synovate.com/news/article/2007/08/new-study-shows-americans-blogging-behaviour.html |publisher=synovate.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815015005/http://www.synovate.com/news/article/2007/08/new-study-shows-americans-blogging-behaviour.html |archivedate=2011-08-15 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, many blogs are highly opinionated and have a [[bias]]. Some are not verified to be true. The [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) established guidelines mandating that bloggers disclose any free goods or services they receive from third parties in 2009 in response to a question of the integrity of product and service reviews in the online community.<ref>http://ftc.gov/os/2009/10/091005revisedendorsementguides.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/10/endortest.shtm|title=FTC Publishes Final Guides Governing Endorsements, Testimonials|work=ftc.gov}}</ref>\n\nThe development of blogging communities has partly resulted because of the lack of local news coverage, the spread of misinformation, and the manipulation of news. Blogging platforms are often used as mediums to spread ideas and connect to others with similar mentalities. Anonymity lives within these platforms that circulates different perspectives. Some have postulated that blogs\u2019 usage of public opinions as facts has gained them status and creditability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molek-Kozakowska|first=Katarzyna|date=August 2013|title=Book review: Digital Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/1750481313485398c|journal=Discourse & Communication|language=en-US|volume=7|issue=3|pages=365\u2013367|doi=10.1177/1750481313485398c|issn=1750-4813}}</ref> Memes are often shared on these blogs due to its social phenomenon and its relation to existing subcultures which often attain high engagement. Traditional journalism has helped set the foundation for blogs, which are frequently used to question mainstream media reported by journalist.\n\n==Citizen journalism==\nDigital journalism's lack of a traditional \"editor\" has given rise to [[citizen journalism]]. The early advances that the digital age offered journalism were faster research, easier editing, conveniences, and a faster delivery time for articles. The Internet has broadened the effect that the digital age has on journalism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Waisbord|first=Silvio|date=2019-03-16|title=The 5Ws and 1H of Digital Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/21670811.2018.1545592|journal=Digital Journalism|volume=7|issue=3|pages=351\u2013358|doi=10.1080/21670811.2018.1545592|issn=2167-0811}}</ref> Because of the popularity of the Internet, most people have access and can add their forms of journalism to the information network. This allows anyone who wants to share something they deem important that has happened in their community. Individuals who are not professional journalists who present news through their blogs or websites are often referred to as citizen journalists. One does not need a <!-- college? -->[[Academic degree|degree]] to be a citizen journalist. Citizen journalists are able to publish information that may not be reported otherwise, and the public has a greater opportunity to be informed. Some companies use the information that a citizen journalist relays when they themselves can not access certain situations, for example, in countries where [[freedom of the press]] is limited. Anyone can [[Internet video|record]] events happening and send it anywhere they wish, or put it on their website. Non-profit and grassroots digital journalism sites may have far fewer resources than their corporate counterparts, yet due to digital media are able to have websites that are technically comparable.<ref>Kawamoto 2003, p. 15.</ref> Other media outlets can then pick up their story and run with it as they please, thus allowing information to reach wider audiences.\n\nFor citizen journalism to be effective and successful, there needs to be citizen editors. Their role being to solicit other people to provide accurate information and to mediate interactivity among users. An example can be found in the start-up of the South Korean online daily newspaper, [[OhMyNews]], where the founder recruited several hundred volunteer \"citizen reporters\" to write news articles that were edited and processed by four professional journalists.<ref>Bentley 2011, p. 107.</ref>\n\n==News collections==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2013}}\nThe Internet also offers options such as personalized news feeds and [[News aggregator|aggregators]], which compile news from different websites into one site. One of the most popular news aggregators is [[Google News]]. Others include  [[Topix.net]], and [[TheFreeLibrary.com]].\n\nBut, some people see too much personalization as detrimental. For example, some fear that people will have narrower exposure to news, seeking out only those commentators who already agree with them.\n\nAs of March 2005, [[Wikinews]] rewrites articles from other news organizations. Original reporting remains a challenge on the Internet as the burdens of verification and legal risks (especially from plaintiff-friendly jurisdictions like BC) remain high in the absence of any net-wide approach to defamation.<ref>O'Grady v. Superior Court, 44 Cal. Rptr. 3d 72, 139 Cal.App. 4th 1423, modified by O'Grady v. Superior Court, 140 Cal.App. 4th 675b, 2006.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Online newspaper]]\n*[[Open source journalism]]\n*[[n:Main Page|Wikinews]]\n*[[Toons Mag]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bentley, Clyde H. 2011. Citizen journalism: Back to the future? ''[[Geopolitics, History, and International Relations]]'' 3 (1): p.&nbsp;103ff.\n* Deuze, Mark. 2003. The web and its journalisms: Considering the consequences of different types of newsmedia online. ''[[New Media & Society]]'' 5 (2): 203-230.\n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2009). El papel decisivo de la banda ancha en el Espacio Iberoamericano del Conocimiento. ''Revista Iberoamericana de Ciencia, Tecnolog\u00eda y Sociedad\u2013CTS'', n. 2, pp.&nbsp;1\u201315.  \n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc (2010). El cloud journalism: un nuevo concepto de producci\u00f3n para el periodismo del siglo XXI. ''Observatorio (OBS*) Journal'', v. 4, n. 1 (2010), pp.&nbsp;19\u201335. \n* Fondevila Gasc\u00f3n, Joan Francesc; Del Olmo Arriaga, Josep Llu\u00eds and Sierra S\u00e1nchez, Javier (2011). New communicative markets, new business models in the digital press. ''Tr\u00edpodos'' (Extra 2011-VI International Conference on Communication and Reality-Life without Media, Universitat Ramon Llull), pp.&nbsp;301\u2013310. \n* Kawamoto, Kevin. 2003. ''Digital Journalism: Emerging Media and the Changing Horizons of Journalism''. Lanham, Md.: Rowman & Littlefield\n* [http://www.ojr.org/ojr/future/1019174689.php Online Journalism Review. 2002. The third wave of online journalism. Online Journalism Review]\n* [http://journalism.about.com/od/citizenjournalism/a/hyperlocal.htm Rogers, Tony. What is hyperlocal journalism? Sites that focus on areas often ignored by larger news outlets\" about.com], accessdate= September 12, 2011\n* Scott, Ben. 2005. A contemporary history of digital journalism. ''[[Television & New Media]]'' 6 (1): 89-126\n* Wall, Melissa. 2005. \"Blogs of war: Weblogs as news.\" ''Journalism'' 6 (2): 153-172\n\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:Online journalism| ]]\n[[Category:Types of journalism]]\n[[Category:Citizen journalism]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Citizen media]]\n[[Category:New media]]\n", "name_user": "Informationtak", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(thedigitalji)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_journalism"}
{"title_page": "Shin Hye-sun", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean actress}}\n{{Korean name|Shin}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Shin Hye-sun\n| image                 = 191231 \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120.jpg\n| caption               = Shin Hye-sun in December 2019\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1989|8|31}}\n| birth_place           = [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| education             = [[Sejong University]] - Film Art\n| other_names = Shin Hae-sun\n| occupation            = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive           = 2012\u2013present\n| agent                 = YNK Entertainment ([[CJ E&M]])\n| spouse                = \n| module                = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes|color=transparent\n| hangul                = {{linktext|\uc2e0|\ud61c\uc120}}\n| hanja                 = {{linktext|\u7533|\u60e0|\u5584}}\n| rr                    = Sin Hyeseon\n| mr                    = Sin Hyes\u014fn\n}}}}\n\n'''Shin Hye-sun''' (born August 31, 1989) is a [[South Korea]]n actress. She made her debut in the [[Korean drama|television series]] ''[[School 2013]]'' and played her first leading role in a drama in ''[[My Golden Life]]'' (2017\u20132018). She gained international recognition through her lead role in ''[[Angel's Last Mission: Love]]'' (2019).\n\n==Career==\nShin Hye-sun debuted as an actress through the TV drama ''[[School 2013]]'', an installment of the long-running ''[[School (South Korean TV series)|School]]'' series, after successfully passing the audition to cast a few schoolgirl roles. She played a minor character with the same name as hers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=404&aid=0000024077|title=[\uc778\ud130\ubdf0] '\ud559\uad50 2013' \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120 \"\uae7b\uc78e\uba38\ub9ac? \uc2e0\uc758 \ud55c \uc218\uc600\uc8e0\"|date=14 February 2013|website=enews24|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nShin began to land bigger roles in 2015 with ''[[Oh My Ghost (2015 TV series)|Oh My Ghost]]'' and ''[[She Was Pretty]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stoo.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=enter3&idxno=2015082108471599919|title='\uc624 \ub098\uc758 \uadc0\uc2e0\ub2d8' \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120 \uc0ac\uace0 \uc804 \ubaa8\uc2b5, \ud720\uccb4\uc5b4\uc5d0 \uac10\ucdb0\uc84c\ub358 \ub298\uc52c\ud55c 8\ub4f1\uc2e0 \ubc1c\ub808\ub9ac\ub098 \uc790\ud0dc [\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\ud22c\ub370\uc774]|date=21 August 2015|website=TV Daily|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hankyung.com/article/201511232668k|title='\uadf8\ub140\ub294 \uc608\ubee4\ub2e4' \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120, \uc774\ud1a0\ub85d '\ud55c\uc124'\uc2a4\ub7ec\uc6b8 \uc218\uac00|date=23 November 2015|website=Hankyung|language=ko}}</ref>\nThough both titles were romantic comedies, her characters varied significantly.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Han|first1=Hye-ri|title=[My Name] \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120 (1)|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/692211|language=ko|website=10asia|accessdate=2017-09-11|date=30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer breakthrough came in 2016 with ''[[Five Enough]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002528013|title=\uc2e0\ud61c\uc120 \"'\uc544\uc774\uac00 \ub2e4\uc12f'\uc11c 7\ub144 \uc9dd\uc0ac\ub791, \uc2e4\uc81c\ub77c\uba74 \ubabb\ud574\uc694\"(\uc778\ud130\ubdf0\u2460)|date=25 May 2016|website=Star Money|language=ko}}</ref> Both her role as a gullible, naively-romantic woman and her pairing with actor [[Sung Hoon]] gained popularity among the viewers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Ji-young|title=''Five Enough'' surpasses 30 percent viewership|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201605161341360408732_2|website=[[The Korea Herald|K-Pop Herald]]|accessdate=2017-09-11|date=16 May 2016}}</ref> The same year, she starred in the fantasy romance drama ''[[The Legend of the Blue Sea]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3022028|title=Actress Shin Hye-sun will join ''Blue Sea''|date=1 August 2016|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she played her first leading film role in ''[[A Day (film)|A Day]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yu|first1=Jiwon|title=\uc2e0\ud61c\uc120, \uc601\ud654 '\ud558\ub8e8' \ud569\ub958..\ubcc0\uc694\ud55c \uc544\ub0b4\ub85c \ucd9c\uc5f0|trans-title=Actress Shin Hye Sun To Play Byun Yo Han's Wife In New Film|url=http://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=108&aid=0002538398|website=Naver|publisher=Star News|accessdate=2016-12-09|date=5 July 2016}}</ref> Shin then played a key figure in an acclaimed [[Crime fiction|crime]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] series ''[[Stranger (TV series)|Stranger]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3029149|title=Shin Hye-sun signs on to ''Secret Forest'' cast|date=26 January 2017|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=[Interview] ''Secret Forest'' Shin Hye-sun, \"I'm lucky to have been in it\"|url=http://www.hancinema.net/interview-secret-forest-sin-hye-seon-i-m-lucky-to-have-been-in-it-108644.html|website=[[HanCinema]]|accessdate=2017-09-11|date=7 August 2017}}</ref> Soon after, she was cast in a protagonist role for the first time with [[KBS2]]'s drama ''[[My Golden Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Park Si-hoo, Shin Hye-sun and Lee Tae-hwan to star in ''My Golden Life''|url=http://www.hancinema.net/park-si-hoo-sin-hye-seon-and-lee-tae-hwan-to-star-in-my-golden-life-107000.html|website=[[HanCinema]]|accessdate=2017-08-21|date=15 June 2017}}</ref> The drama was a major hit in South Korea and surpassed 40% ratings,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201712111322170126933_2|title='My Golden Life' tops viewer ratings of 41.2%|date=11 December 2017|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> leading to increased recognition for Shin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2017/11/688_238987.html|title=Tough cookie Cinderellas win viewers' hearts|date=8 November 2017|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/03/31/2018033100375.html|title=Actress Shin Hye-sun Finds Success Brings New Pressures|date=31 March 2018|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Shin was cast in the drama special ''[[The Hymn of Death]]'' in the role of [[Yun Sim-deok]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201811020849214530273_2|title=Lee Jong-suk, Shin Hye-sun to appear in 'Hymn of Death'|date=2 November 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> She also starred in the romance comedy drama ''[[Still 17]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3048218&cloc=joongangdaily|title=Shin Hae-sun, Yang Se-jong cast in SBS show|date=17 May 2018|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> The same year, she was cast in the legal film ''Innocent''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002740473|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\uc2e0\ud61c\uc120, '\uacb0\ubc31'\uc73c\ub85c \uc2a4\ud06c\ub9b0 \uccab \uc8fc\uc5f0..\u00b7\ubc30\uc885\uc625\uacfc \ud638\ud761|date=8 November 2018|website=Star News|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Shin starred in the fantasy romance drama ''[[Angel's Last Mission: Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000694758|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc9d5] \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120, '\ub2e8, \ud558\ub098\uc758 \uc0ac\ub791' \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815\u2026\uc5f4\uc77c \ud589\ubcf4|date=11 December 2018|website=Sports Donga|language=ko}}</ref> The same year, she was cast in the film ''Tomb Robbery''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/lee-je-hoon-jo-woo-jin-im-won-hee-and-shin-hye-sun-reportedly-up-for-tomb-robbery-129426.html|title=Lee Je-hoon, Jo Woo-jin, Im Won-hee and Shin Hye-sun Reportedly up for \"Tomb Robbery\"|date=8 May 2019|website=Hancinema}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| ''One Summer Night''\n| So-ra\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Short film|Short films]]\n|-\n| ''Return Match''\n| Joo-yeon\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[A Violent Prosecutor]]''\n| Yoon-ah\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[A Day (film)|A Day]]''\n| Mi-kyung\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2020\n| ''Innocence''\n| Ahn Jung-in\n|\n|-\n| ''Tomb Robbery''\n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2012\u201313\n| ''[[School 2013]]''\n| Shin Hye-sun\n| [[KBS2]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| ''[[Angel Eyes (TV series)|Angel Eyes]]''\n| young Cha Min-soo\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[High School King of Savvy]]''\n| Go Yoon-joo\n| [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=119&aid=0002225901|title='\uace0\uad50\ucc98\uc138\uc655' \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120-\uc774\uc8fc\uc2b9, \uaca9\ud55c \ud0a4\uc2a4\uc2e0 \uc7ac\uc870\uba85 \uc774\uc720\ub294?|date=3 December 2014|website=Dailian|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\u201315\n| ''Forever Young''\n| Han Mi-so\n| [[VTV3]]\n| Korean-Vietnamese production<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enews24.tving.com/star/article?nsID=779031|title=\ubca0\ud2b8\ub0a8 \ub300\ubc15 \ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\uc624\ub298\ub3c4 \uccad\ucd98', \ub4dc\ub514\uc5b4 \uc654\ub2e4..\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub9ac\uc628 \uc790\ub9c9 \ubc29\uc1a1|date=11 June 2015|website=enews24|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| ''[[Oh My Ghost (2015 TV series)|Oh My Ghost]]''\n| Kang Eun-hee\n| tvN\n|\n|-\n| ''[[She Was Pretty]]''\n| Han Seol\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n| ''[[Five Enough]]''\n| Lee Yeon-tae\n| KBS2\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Legend of the Blue Sea]]''\n| Cha Si-ah\n| SBS\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Stranger (TV series)|Stranger]]''\n| Young Eun-soo\n| tvN\n|\n|-\n| 2017\u201318\n| ''[[My Golden Life]]''\n| Seo Ji-an\n| KBS2\n| First leading role\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2018\n| ''[[Still 17]]''\n| Woo Seo-ri\n| rowspan=2| SBS\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Hymn of Death]]''\n| [[Yun Sim-deok]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Angel's Last Mission: Love]]''\n| Lee Yeon-seo\n| KBS2\n|\n|}2020\n| ''[[Historical Fusion]]\n\n| Tvn\n\n===Music video appearance===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2013 || \"Curious\" || What Women Want ft. Jung-yup from [[Brown Eyed Soul (band)|Brown Eyed Soul]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=215&aid=0000391925|title='\uadf8\ub140\ub294 \uc608\ubee4\ub2e4' \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120, '\ubb34\ud73c' \uc724\uade0\uc0c1\uacfc \ub2ec\ub2ec \uc5f0\uc778 \ucf00\ubbf8 \ud3ed\ubc1c \"\ud6c8\ub0a8\ud6c8\ub140\"|date=11 November 2015|website=WowTV|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/531199wpp/vocal-group-what-women-want-debut-with-music-video-for-curious/|title=Vocal Group What Women Want Debut with Music Video for \"Curious\"|date=17 September 2013|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Feel Like\" \n|[[Naul (singer)|Naul]] \n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0003014352|title=\ub098\uc5bc \uce21 \"\uc815\uaddc2\uc9d1 \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0 '\ub110 \ubd80\ub974\ub294 \ubc24', MV \uc5ec\uc8fc\ub294 \uc2e0\ud61c\uc120\"(\uacf5\uc2dd)|date=26 March 2018|website=Herald Pop|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Snowfall\"\n|[[g.o.d]]\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1270047wpp/watch-g-o-d-sings-snowfall-emotional-mv-starring-shin-hye-sun-kim-dong-wook|title=Watch: g.o.d Sings Of A \"Snowfall\" In Emotional MV Starring Shin Hye Sun And Kim Dong Wook|website=Soompi|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[2015 MBC Drama Awards|MBC Drama Awards]]\n| Best New Actress in a Miniseries\n| ''[[She Was Pretty]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|2016\n| 2nd [[Scene Stealer Festival]]\n| Rookie of the Year\n| ''[[Five Enough]]'', ''[[A V