un}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean film actresses]]\n[[Category:South Korean television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Seoul]]\n[[Category:Sejong University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "151.245.118.157", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shin_Hye-sun"}
{"title_page": "Berman brothers (painters)", "text_new": "{{About|the painters|the American songwriters/producers|Berman Brothers (producers)}}\n{{Short description|Russian painters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Eugene Berman 1960s2.jpg|thumb|Eugene Berman in Italy in the 1960s]]\n'''Eug\u00e8ne Berman''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d|links=no}}; 4 November 1899, [[Saint Petersburg, Russia]] \u2013 14 December 1972, Rome) and his brother '''Leonid Berman''' were [[Russians|Russian]] [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-romantic]] [[Painting|painter]]s and theater and opera designers.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in Russia, the Bermans fled the [[Russian revolution]] in 1918.  In Paris the Bermans exhibited at the Galerie Pierre where their work earned them the name \"[[Neo-Romantic]]s\" for its melancholy and introspective qualities, having taken inspiration from the Blue Period paintings of [[Pablo Picasso]].  Other Neo-Romantic painters were [[Christian B\u00e9rard]], [[Pavel Tchelitchev]], [[Kristians Tonny]] and, later in America, their friend Muriel Streeter (wife of their art dealer [[Julien Levy]]).\n\nEug\u00e8ne's work was characterized by lonely landscapes featuring sculptural and architectural elements, often ruins, rendered in a [[Neo-classicism|neo-classical]] manner<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.caldwellgallery.com/artists/eugene-berman/biography|title=Eugene Berman {{!}} Caldwell Gallery|website=www.caldwellgallery.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, whereas that of Leonid depicted beaches with fisherman's boats and nets in many parts of the world.  In 1935 Eug\u00e8ne left for New York where he exhibited frequently at the [[Julien Levy Gallery]] (as did Leonid after the war). Later, in the 1940s, Eug\u00e8ne settled in Los Angeles and married the actress [[Ona Munson]],<ref name=\":0\" /> while Leonid remained in New York and married the harpsichordist [[Sylvia Marlowe]]. In 1950 he exhibited at Instituto de Arte Moderno, [[Buenos Aires]]. In 1950, Berman was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full member in 1954.\n\n==Later years and death==\nIn America, Eug\u00e8ne became well known as a [[stage designer]] for ballet and opera.  Following the suicide of his wife in 1955, he moved to [[Rome]] where Princess Doria-Pamphilj provided an apartment and studio for him in a wing of her palazzo on the via del Corso.  He continued to paint there until his death in 1972.<ref name=\":0\" /> Leonid died in New York in 1976.\n\n=== Works ===\n* ''[[Tschaikovsky Piano Concerto No. 2 (ballet)|Ballet Imperial]]'' by [[George Balanchine]], [[Sadler's Wells Ballet]], London (1950).\n\n==Legacy==\nEugene Berman's work can be found in a number of institutions, including: \n* [[McNay Art Museum]] <ref>{{cite web|author1=McNay Art Museum|title=McNay Collection: Eugene Berman|url=http://collection.mcnayart.org/search.do?view=lightbox&collection=7&field-0=simpleSearchObject&bool-0=AND&keyword-0=Eugene+Berman|publisher=Mcnayart.org|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2014}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]]<ref name=\"MoMA\">{{cite web|author1=The Museum of Modern Art|title=MoMA Collection: Eugene Berman|url=http://www.moma.org/collection/artists/502?locale=en|publisher=MoMA.org|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n*[[Art Institute of Chicago]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=The Art Institute of Chicago|title=Collections: Berman, Eugene|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Berman%2C+Eugene|publisher=Artic.edu|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n*[[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden|title=Collection Search: Eugene Berman|url=http://hirshhorn.si.edu/search-results/?edan_search_value=eugene+berman&edan_search_button=Search+Collection#|publisher=hirshhorn.si.edu|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian B\u00e9rard]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Eugene Berman}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berman, Eugene}}\n[[Category:Russian painters]]\n[[Category:Russian male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:Jewish painters]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian designers]]\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sibling artists]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Sibling duos]]\n[[Category:19th-century male artists]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-1890s-stub}}\n{{Russia-artist-stub}}\n{{France-painter-19thC-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the painters|the American songwriters/producers|Berman Brothers (producers)}}\n{{Short description|Russian painters}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Eugene Berman 1960s2.jpg|thumb|Eugene Berman in Italy in the 1960s]]\n'''Eug\u00e8ne Berman''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d|links=no}}; 4 November 1899, [[Saint Petersburg, Russia]] \u2013 14 December 1972, Rome) and his brother '''Leonid Berman''' were [[Russians|Russian]] [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-romantic]] [[Painting|painter]]s and theater and opera designers.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in Russia, the Bermans fled the [[Russian revolution]] in 1918.  In Paris the Bermans exhibited at the Galerie Pierre where their work earned them the name \"[[Neo-Romantic]]s\" for its melancholy and introspective qualities, having taken inspiration from the Blue Period paintings of [[Pablo Picasso]].  Other Neo-Romantic painters were [[Christian B\u00e9rard]], [[Pavel Tchelitchev]], [[Kristians Tonny]] and, later in America, their friend Muriel Streeter (wife of their art dealer [[Julien Levy]]).\n\nEug\u00e8ne's work was characterized by lonely landscapes featuring sculptural and architectural elements, often ruins, rendered in a [[Neo-classicism|neo-classical]] manner, whereas that of Leonid depicted beaches with fisherman's boats and nets in many parts of the world.  In 1935 Eug\u00e8ne left for New York where he exhibited frequently at the [[Julien Levy Gallery]] (as did Leonid after the war). Later, in the 1940s, Eug\u00e8ne settled in Los Angeles and married the actress [[Ona Munson]], while Leonid remained in New York and married the harpsichordist [[Sylvia Marlowe]]. In 1950 he exhibited at Instituto de Arte Moderno, [[Buenos Aires]]. In 1950, Berman was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full member in 1954.\n\n==Later years and death==\nIn America, Eug\u00e8ne became well known as a [[stage designer]] for ballet and opera.  Following the suicide of his wife in 1955, he moved to [[Rome]] where Princess Doria-Pamphilj provided an apartment and studio for him in a wing of her palazzo on the via del Corso.  He continued to paint there until his death in 1972. Leonid died in New York in 1976.\n\n=== Works ===\n* ''[[Tschaikovsky Piano Concerto No. 2 (ballet)|Ballet Imperial]]'' by [[George Balanchine]], [[Sadler's Wells Ballet]], London (1950).\n\n==Legacy==\nEugene Berman's work can be found in a number of institutions, including: \n* [[McNay Art Museum]] <ref>{{cite web|author1=McNay Art Museum|title=McNay Collection: Eugene Berman|url=http://collection.mcnayart.org/search.do?view=lightbox&collection=7&field-0=simpleSearchObject&bool-0=AND&keyword-0=Eugene+Berman|publisher=Mcnayart.org|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2014}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]]<ref name=\"MoMA\">{{cite web|author1=The Museum of Modern Art|title=MoMA Collection: Eugene Berman|url=http://www.moma.org/collection/artists/502?locale=en|publisher=MoMA.org|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n*[[Art Institute of Chicago]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=The Art Institute of Chicago|title=Collections: Berman, Eugene|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Berman%2C+Eugene|publisher=Artic.edu|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n*[[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden|title=Collection Search: Eugene Berman|url=http://hirshhorn.si.edu/search-results/?edan_search_value=eugene+berman&edan_search_button=Search+Collection#|publisher=hirshhorn.si.edu|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christian B\u00e9rard]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Eugene Berman}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berman, Eugene}}\n[[Category:Russian painters]]\n[[Category:Russian male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:Jewish painters]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian designers]]\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sibling artists]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Sibling duos]]\n[[Category:19th-century male artists]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-1890s-stub}}\n{{Russia-artist-stub}}\n{{France-painter-19thC-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cynthia Wing", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added additional source.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berman_brothers_(painters)"}
